<td align="left" width="100%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="white" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: bold;">FIRST EARTHDAWN PUBLICATIONS ROSTER POSTED</font></td>
</tr>
<tr bgcolor="#8080a6">
<td width="100%">
<p align="right">
<i><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="#ffffff" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: bold;">By James Flowers,
          22 October 2003</font></i>
</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr bgcolor="#dfdfdf">
<td align="left" width="100%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px">RedBrick has posted their first Earthdawn Publications Roster onto their web site for download (see the Publications link to the right). Comments and feedback welcome (see the Contact Us page for details).</font></td>
</tr>
<td align="right" width="100%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px" size="-1"><a href="http://www.earthdawn-classic.com:80/readMore.html?id=146">Go back to article</a></font></td>
</table>
<br>
 
   
 
<table width="100%">
<tr>
<td align="center" bgcolor="#8080a6" width="100%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="#ffffff" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: bold;" size="+1"><b>Comments</b></font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<table width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#8080a6">
<td width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="#ffffff" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: bold;"><b>Author</b></font></td><td width="80%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="#ffffff" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: bold;"><b>Discussion</b></font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<table width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#dfdfdf">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>Tarliman</b>
<br>21 October 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>Publication Schedule</b>
<br>
<p>Ambitious, but well organized. Looks like you've thoroughly considered the reorganization of the extant material, bringing it all together in ways that make good sense. The schedule is heavy on location books, which is excellent, as I'm always in need of location materials as a GM. It's a bit light on scenarios, would like to see more adventures, especially introductory and low-Circle stuff. Is there a Demo Kit in there somewhere, with a stripped-down ruleset, a sign-up sheet, a window flyer, and pregenerated characters? The FASA demo kit was very useful in getting new players interested in the game system.</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<table width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#C1BEC9">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>Richard Vowles</b>
<br>21 October 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>Publication Schedule</b>
<br>
<p>The scenarios and introductory stuff wasn't included by James this time around. It is intended to be in his next iteration. The FASA demo kit may just be online some time soon :-)<p></p>Richard</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<table width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#dfdfdf">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>James Flowers</b>
<br>22 October 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>Publication Schedule</b>
<br>
<p>Hi Tarliman,<p></p>What Richard said. *grin* There are plans to produce more scenarios, and for use with a wide range of Circles. We intend to have several demo kits available, and there is a supplementary online program to support both the web site (with free downloads) and published material (material that didn't make the cut, additional goodies, etc).<p></p>Rest assured we're working to get "real" products out as soon as possible.<p></p>Kind regards,<br>JAMES FLOWERS<br>Line Developer, RedBrick Limited</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
 
